column51: I get confused by the number of Scholastic sites there are to shop at. First I logged into the regular Scholastic site and was shopping, but then I realized I wasn't using the same website as what was on the flyer my daughter got from her teacher (scholastic.com/bookclubs). The same login works on both sites, but I wasn't able to find the same books on both sites. BUT, the books on the site from the flyer were cheaper than on the regular site. Seemed odd, but I'm not complaining...

column7: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/112.0.0.0 Safari/537.36
column51: I am super disappointed that teachers don't get their $10 to spend RIGHT NOW and we receive a $10 coupon in the book box to spend for NEXT month.   I teach at a low income school, so I do not send home book orders every month, but rather every other month.  I don't need another reason for parents to say no to their child when they can't financially afford to order books all the time.   If anything, this hurts ME, the teacher.  I waste my $10 coupon because I don't want to spend more of my own money to pay for shipping.  Please go back to your old method and don't hurt us teachers!!!

column51: I love Scholastic! I think there are great options for books and the prices are very reasonable.   Two suggestions: One suggestion I have is having a lower grade level book and an upper grade level book for the $1 books each week. There was a lot of lower level books this year and my 4th graders were past that. I would have ordered more books if there were more 4th grade level book options.   Second suggestion: the $1 books that were picked this year for the upper grades did not align with their interests. A lot of the books are classics but do not seem interesting to them so we didn't order.
